## HTML basics

HyperText Markup Language
	- hypertext: text with links

Anatomy of an HTML element

opening tag     content     closing tag
<foo> ...................... </foo>
elementelementelementelementelementelement

+attributes

Some elements can be nested, refer to HTML5 for details. (Or use static analysis.)

Some elements are 'empty', they don't have to be closed.

<img src=...>



Anatomy of an HTML document

<!DOCTYPE html>  // mandatory
<html>  // sometimes called root
<head>   // container for metadata
	<meta>  // metadata
<body>  // the visible part


## CSS Basics

style sheet
- manual detailing the house style of a particular publisher, publication, etc.

- 'the cascade', the priority scheme that is used to merge styles from different places, specificity etc

- to fall, pour, or rush in or as if in a cascade

ruleset ("rule"): selector { declarations (property: property_value;) }

selectors: 
a, b, c = a or b or c


CSS: All about boxes

padding border margin
width, background-color, color, text-shadow, display

property: 0  // one value affects all 4 sides
property: x y // x affects top/bottom, y affects left/right
property: x y z // top, horizontal, bottom
property: x y z w // top, right, bottom, left

padding syntax: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/padding#syntax


CSS Units:
cm/mm/in/px/pt/pc: absolute IRL length
relative lengths:
	em: element font size
	ex: element font x-height
	ch: width of the zero glyph
	rem: relative to root element font size
	vw: 1% of viewport width
	vh: 1% of viewport height
	vmin: 1% of viewport's smallest dimension
	vmin: 1% of viewport's largest dimension
	%: relative to parent element (think about relative/absolute)


CSS display:
https://www.w3schools.com/cssref/pr_class_display.asp
"type of rendering box"	


https://www.w3.org/TR/WD-CSS2-971104/box.html
https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/CSS_Box_Model/Introduction_to_the_CSS_box_model

If the box-sizing property is set to content-box (default) and if the element is a block element, the content area's size can be explicitly defined with the width, min-width, max-width, height, min-height, and max-height properties.

https://drafts.csswg.org/css-box/#intro

flex-box


display values:
- inline, like span (height and width have no effect)
- block, like p (starts on new line and takes up all width)
- contents, makes the container disappear, making the children elements of the parent
- flex, block-level flex container (for positioning chilren)
- grid, block-level grid-container
- inline-block, formatted as inline â€” but you can set width and height
- inline-flex, ...
- inline-grid, ...
- inline-table, displayed as an inline-level grid container
- list-item, let the element behave like a <li> element
- run-in, displays as block or inline, depending on context
- table, behave like table
- table-{caption,column-group,header-group,footer-group,row-group,cell,column,tr}, like these parts
	The <col> tag is useful for applying styles to entire columns, instead of repeating the styles for each cell, for each row.
- none, the element is completely removed
- initial, reset to default value
- inherit, inherit from parent


visibility: hidden, still there but not shown. Positioned / takes up space.

